node.text: TGIF, amirite? Lots of new faces around here - so allow me to (re)introduce myself, and hopefully I can get to learn a little bit about some of you, too. My name is Nicolette (sometimes Nic, rarely Nikki, NEVER Nicole). I‚Äôm a Los Angeles native and moved to NYC in 2004, and for the last few years have split the majority of my life between those two cities. I‚Äôm a Taurus, Leo rising, Libra moon - and am celebrating my 33rd birthday very soon. I‚Äôm very, very gay and for some reason that still surprises people.  I love color (even though I wear black on most days), pugs, and would choose tacos or sushi over almost any other foods. I think pink is a neutral. I started my career as a brand strategist and designer, and started blogging around that same time as a hobby - which eventually, somehow, lead to working in fashion media - including being a contributing editor and columnist at Marie Claire for 5 years. I co-founded @premme.us with my bff and biz partner @gabifresh, where we make some bad ass clothes for size 12+ babes. I love to laugh, and try to learn something new every day. I am so excited to share that the campaign I shot with @ultabeauty has been rolled out NATION WIDE in ulta beauty stores!! I can‚Äôt believe it; it feels completely surreal to walk into a store and see my reflection looking back at me in a beauty context. I literally welled up in tears when I saw the signage for the first time, (seriously: head to my story for my candid reaction caught on camera). It immediately sent me down this path of wondering what life would have been like had I grown up with images that reflected me, with bodies that looked like mine, to feel affirmed and validated in my physical body when I first started navigating my love of makeup when I was 13 years old. It‚Äôs hard not to get emotional about this - but I made a promise to myself a while ago that everything I do in my career would be in service to my younger self. This is for her. #ad #ultabeauty

"Self-care" isn't all bath bombs and face masks. Trust me, I love a good bath and a solid moisturizing mask, but for me, self-care has become more about spreadsheets (hello, adulthood) and work-outs. Whether it's taking a walk around the neighborhood mid-day during work hours, or getting myself up before the crack of dawn to jump on a 6AM spin session, I've learned the importance of breaking a sweat in order to realign my body and mind. It is such a necessary part of my mental health routine! While I'm not really one for "resolutions," I do love goals - so I've been challenging myself to get active and move more throughout the day. My @fossil sport smartwatch allows me to set custom goals, and track them, that are actually realistic and beneficial for me - all while tracking my heart rate and allowing me to set little reminders like drinking more water throughout the day, too. The theme for 2018 for me has been HEALING. Big time. It was important for me to heal (for me, how other people navigate their lives is entirely their choice) before opening up about my vulnerabilities and pain points. 2017 was one of the best years of my life professionally, but absolutely my hardest, most challenging year on a personal level - an imbalance that in and of itself felt like a confrontational rollercoaster. There were so many enormous shifts - I went through a separation, decided to sell and move out of the home we shared in LA, my entire career life shifted rapidly, I developed new autoimmune issues, and my whole world very quickly felt like it was upside down. I wasn‚Äôt ready to answer questions like ‚Äúwhat happened?‚Äù ‚Äî as if there‚Äôs a simple answer, or even owed that to anyone but myself. Some things are best kept private, but I will say: we‚Äôre still close and have a lot of love for each other. Then 2018 came knocking and I knew it was time to focus on rebuilding, all wabi-sabi and full of imperfections and transience and change. And I feel good, now. Really good. I‚Äôm more confident, stronger, more patient, trusting myself and my intuition more. I committed myself back to therapy, said ‚Äúno‚Äù to more things to say ‚Äúyes‚Äù to myself, spent more time with my family, learned how to ask for help and support and patience, and got really fucking good at crying it out and processing all my feelings. So many of my friends have been facing similar changes, and that sense of community and knowing I‚Äôm not alone has made all the difference - and maybe it will help for one of you to know you‚Äôre not alone, either. Not everything has to be forever to have still been a really good time. And hey, everyone gets hyper reflective this time of year, right?! Nothing but gratitude for this process üñ§

You know how I (and everyone, basically) always say ‚Äúbody positivity is a journey‚Äù? I‚Äôve been echoing that back to myself on repeat recently. A combination of stress, a major shift in my routine, and the fact that I‚Äôve PROBABLY replaced all the water I usually drink with coffee, have made me not really feel like myself these past couple of months, and even actively feel sort of... not great. It‚Äôs really bizarre to not recognize yourself when part of your job is to put yourself out there ‚Äî and then feel so stifled that you accidentally stop doing it entirely. I was talking about this yesterday with a friend and had to really remind myself that the things we see or criticize or nit pick in ourselves are not things other people would ever even notice. Be kind to yourself, and if you‚Äôre going through it with weird self-image feelings, know that you‚Äôre definitely not alone!

Today is #nationalcomingoutday and I‚Äôm using this day as an excuse to post this fabulous rainbow dress AGAIN because IT‚ÄôS AMAZING üåà For most people, coming out is not a singular event. I basically come out every single day, and having the safety to do so is an enormous luxury and a privilege. I have, literally, dozens of coming out stories ‚Äî but the first of them was when I came out to my best friend, Emily, when I was 15 years old and instant messaged her to tell her I was ‚Äúpretty sure I liked girls.‚Äù Her response? ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs gross.‚Äù And then like a week and a half later she instant messaged me to be like, ‚Äújk, I like girls too.‚Äù Like, hello - I didn‚Äôt just randomly select a girl on my waterpolo team (hint #1) to come out to without having my gaydar go off a little. It wasn‚Äôt until many years later that I would actually feel comfortable identifying as gay, and it took even longer to understand my identity and how I could embody it in the world - what it meant or looked like to be femme, or to possess a multitude of identities, or to frame my own sense of self in a world where I saw little visibility of the possibilities of who I could be. 
Having the choice to opt in or out of coming out is, in itself, a privilege. Coming out is not yet an option for everyone to do safely, and NO ONE should ever feel pressured to come out. There‚Äôs no roadmap or instruction book on how to be you, whatever or whoever that is. I had a much needed (but still outrageously busy!) couple of weeks in New York. I'm back in LA now, and reflecting on the time I spent with friends, queer community, peers & colleagues, and collaborating with fellow makers. It has been a tumultuous year for me; I've been down the path of many existential thought processes where I've challenged myself to think about where I'm most at home (hello, Saturn return). What makes me feel most comfortable and at ease, where (geographically) am i most myself, and in what ways do I feel best in inhabiting my own body? Partnering with @elomilingerie and working with artist @sumajanedark on a portrait project had me confront many of those questions and really check in with myself. Old insecurities that I thought I'd long said goodbye to had started creeping in again. Self-love isn't always a sure thing; sometimes it ebbs and flows and we're challenged to love ourselves, and sometimes our surroundings and context have a great impact on that. Seeing myself in these elomi pieces, and shooting with my friend @lydiahudgens for a fun, intimate, carefree moment in my home, brought me back to myself -- and it's a self I'm learning to fall in love with all over again. #elomiallyou

Even with all the privilege I have in navigating the world (my middle eastern heritage is hidden behind my pale skin, my queer identity is often invisible, and I'm of able body), I've been challenged by the external limitations imposed onto me. Whether it was in pursuing specific sports as a child, or in dreaming about working in fashion as a young adult - I've been told that certain things weren't "for me." I wonder what it would look like if we heard "yes" more than "no" in the pursuit of our dreams? It's all part of why feminism, gender equality, and visibility of marginalized voices and identities are all so important to me. Writing about this and more on my blog, in partnership with @proctergamble. #loveoverbias #ad

A few weeks ago I met @sumajanedark in LA to shoot portraits with her in collaboration with @elomilingerie. I'm not going to lie - even though I'm in front of the camera all the time, I always get really nervous whenever I shoot with a new photographer, especially when I don't know exactly what to expect. Elomi partnered with 5 women artists to each create portraits that showed a more intimate portrait of their assigned muse. Suma wanted to explore the ways we see ourselves versus the way the world sees us -- and I realized my nervousness was, at least in part, rooted in being forced to confront that I still worry to some extent about how other people view me. Suma had a whole crew taking portraits of me from different angles while I was taking selfies and then layered them all together in one composition. I always remind people that self-confidence is a journey, and everyone - EVERYONE, has good days and bad days where they feel self-conscious. I guess photoshoot days are still one of mine, but I loved how Suma's piece turned out, and seeing how people responded to it was a really empowering moment. You can visit the gallery at 393 Broadway in TriBeCa until Friday! #elomiallyou

Growing up, sports was always a huge source of confidence for me - and where I made so many of my lifelong friends. In high school, I was a swimmer and played on the water polo team, and though I was battling so much internally, like figuring out my sexuality and how that was part of my identity, it also lead me to a life changing friendship with someone who still, 16 years later, is one of my best friends. We were the first people to come out to each other, and without connecting through sports, I know navigating our teenage years would have felt much more lonely and isolating. Now, it is so important for me to connect with other LGBTQ youth and advocate for their wellbeing. For any person who feels different or experiences marginalization, visibility, peer-to-peer connection, and mentorship is so essential to building self-esteem. During the month of October, @PlanetFitness is promoting its pro-kindness, anti-bullying initiative, the Judgment Free Generation, in collaboration with Boys & Girls Clubs of America (@bgca). Moment of joy: Frankie. And. Me. In. Matching. OUTFITS. 
It's hard not to feel heartbroken when there's so much grief and tragedy happening in our world. A thing I've been doing to help elevate my own mood: reminding myself of the places I find joy and expressing gratitude, and asking others to share their own joy with me. I love my family and friends SO MUCH. I love animals, especially my cat and dog, and especially that I can have silly, playful moments with Frankie like dressing up in matching jackets. I love this time of year when the air turns just a little more brisk, and I walk aimlessly exploring throughout Brooklyn. I love my community and the ways we reach out and lean on each other in times of crisis and of celebration. I love my work, and that I get the chance to be creative every single day. I love the ritual of swiping on a bright red lipstick and lining my lids and piling on my femme armor. Healing and self-care look different for everyone, but I hope these little things help someone. Sending you all love and strength, and if you feel up to it, please share a few things that bring YOU joy.

#DoYouStories Ever since I was a young girl, I‚Äôve been obsessed with fashion. When my friends started reading teen celeb mags, I gravitated towards Vogue and Harpers Bazaar, and fawned over the editorial spreads that would soon become wallpaper plastered from floor to ceiling of my bedroom. I almost never saw anyone who looked like me in the pages of these magazines, but I couldn‚Äôt help but fall in love with the art and architecture of fashion, and the ways that clothes could evoke or communicate a feeling. As I grew up and into my own identity, fashion became a major part of how I self-expressed; my outfits were a way of communicating little parts of myself through subtle cues, colors, and patterns. Fashion only became a bigger part of identity when I moved to New York and started school at Parsons, but even then - the lack of visibility that I could resonate with made me shy away from pursuing a career in fashion. Fast forward nearly a decade later, and I‚Äôve somehow been in dozens of magazines and this past week, launched a clothing brand with one of my best friends. These last few weeks have been completely surreal: everything about mine and Gabi's journey with launching @premme.us has been centered around the idea of empowerment - that we all deserve to be seen, heard, visible, valued, and find joy in getting dressed. There's no wrong way to be a woman, no wrong way to be femme, and no wrong way to be queer. So much of impacting social progress and change is in uplifting diverse stories, creating media that promotes visibility, and reflecting our world in a way that emphasizes the value of each of our individual identities and lives. I'm proud to partner with @secretdeodorant, who embody that message through campaigns like their moving and impactful "Ladies Room" spot, which featured a breakthrough moment of a transwoman, Dana. Thanks to everyone who joined me on my fb livestream to discuss the power of visibility and how we can all strive to be better allies to our lgbtq siblings! 14 years ago today, June 29th, I got off a red-eye to New York to spend the summer at Parsons, before my senior year of high school. It was also the day of the New York City Pride parade, and after dropping my bags at my dorm, I headed straight for 5th Avenue and the West Village to watch the colorful masses descend upon my adopted hometown. Moving to NYC was a turning point for me; it was the first time and place where I felt like I could be unapologetically myself, where I had the space to explore all the facets of my identity, and where I found my "people." It makes sense that NYC would then be the place where I would start my career, fall in love many times, and share my love and sense of pride in myself with my friends and family. "Pride" exists because having space to be ourselves is not a given for everyone, especially when many of us are told there is something inherently wrong with who we are. Visibility and being "out" is still not safe for everyone, and my greatest wish is that we can work each day to make the world a safer place for everyone to be themselves - whatever that looks like. For me, my personhood and womanhood will forever be attached to the fact that I'm queer, that I'm femme, that I live in this body, that I was born into a mixed family with a multitude of inherited traditions and cultures. This pride season, @SecretDeodorant is reminding us all that there is No Wrong Way to Be a Woman. This morning at 10AM PST, I'll be going live on facebook (facebook.com/nicolettemasonblog) to share my coming out story, all the ways Pride is important to me, and a beautiful spot by Secret that brought me to tears (link in bio!). I hope you will join me! Happy pride, everyone! #stresstest #secretpartner #sponsored

Thinking a lot about how depending on the shape of our bodies or our assigned sex (or a million other things about our physical selves) - that we are "allowed," or not, to participate in specific activities. ‚ú®CALL YOUR SENATORS!‚ú® Feeling especially grateful & inspired by my sister @janetmock this morning, & hoping you will read her words, because what happened yesterday is an infringement on the rights of all LGBTQ people. I hope you will join us to #protecttranskids:
"I just read the news that the Trump administration decided to roll back protections for trans students, and it weighs heavily on me. 
I was in the seventh grade when I first vocalized that I was trans. I began socially transitioning in middle school, medically transitioning as a freshman, and reintroduced myself as Janet as a sophomore at a welcome back ceremony. I was our class treasurer, captain of the volleyball team, and played tuba in the marching band. 
Like all young people, I was growing comfortable in my own skin while discovering what I loved, what I wanted to do, who I wanted to be and what I felt I could do. Sure, my identity and body struggles made my coming-of-age unique and much more visible than my peers, but my classmates and I all had our own struggles, paths and journeys. 
I knew as a young person that it was vital for all students to feel safe, welcomed and affirmed, and I had my own experiences, which I detailed in my first memoir Redefining Realness, that made school -- a place that I once considered a refuge -- incredibly difficult for me to even attend. 
I had issues with bathrooms and locker room access. I was sent home repeatedly due to ‚Äúdress code violations.‚Äù I was repeatedly called out of my name and misgendered daily by classmates and staff. 
Always the first with my hand up, the one ready and willing to do and learn more, I would go home at night and seriously contemplate never returning to school. The struggle of waking up every day, getting dressed, walking to school and being met with stares and closed doors weighed heavily on me. I was only 15 years old.
Eventually, with the help of my mother, I transferred to a school that was affirming and welcoming, one that actually advocated for me. It was at Farrington High School, where I was given equal access to facilities, called by my name, assured and left with a full-ride academic scholarship to college. (Continued)

I'm still processing all my feelings, inspiration, and thoughts on this weekend's women's march. I want the momentum that I felt and that has been built to transcend this moment in time, far beyond Saturday and beyond the next 4 years. I want women's voices to be centered - especially those of indigenous women, women of color, trans women, women with disabilities, and others who experience marginalization in their every day lives. I want us all to march when black and brown lives are targeted, (will you come with me to the next BLM rally?). I want us to all march for clean air and water and to demand investment in renewable energy. I want us to fight for education and health care and housing for all. I want all my LGBTQ+ siblings to know their lives are valued. I want us to not boil feminism down to genitalia and leave gender essentialism in the past. I want the fear I felt in coming home after the March and seeing the press secretary blatantly lie to the country, and having it spun into "alternative facts," to translate into action. I want to create change, and I want to organize, and I know I don't have all the answers yet on how and where to do that, but I know that the reinstatement of the global gag rule on reproductive rights is a critical place for me to focus my energy right now. If you made it into the streets this weekend to share your voice, can you please promise me you'll stay committed to fighting for equal rights for ALL? Please? We have to take this energy, create real change together, and make a commitment to leave no one behind. (PS, if anyone knows the rainbow lady liberty above, can you please tag them? We exchanged quick "thank you"s after I snapped this pic but I'd love to credit them properly!)

One of my favorite friends/people in the universe, @janetmock, spoke at the Women's March in DC today. I could not be more proud of my sister, her brilliance, her words, and her power in sharing her truth with the world.  Below an excerpt of her incredible speech: Our approach to freedom need not be identical but it must be intersectional and inclusive. It must extend beyond ourselves. I know with surpassing certainty that my liberation is directly linked to the liberation of the undocumented trans Latina yearning for refuge. The disabled student seeking unequivocal access. The sex worker fighting to make her living safely.

Collective liberation and solidarity is difficult work. It is work that will find us struggling together and struggling with one another. Just because we are oppressed does not mean that we do not ourselves fall victim to enacting the same unconscious policing, shaming, and erasing. We must return to one another with greater accountability and commitment to the work today.

By being here you are making a commitment to this work. Together we are creating a resounding statement, a statement that stakes a claim on our lives and our loves, our bodies and our babies, our identities and our ideals. But a movement ‚Äì a movement is so much more than a march. A movement is that difficult space between our reality and our vision. Our liberation depends on all of us, all of us returning to our homes and using this experience and all the experiences that have shaped us to act, to organize, to resist.
This is what democracy looks like. üíó üì∏ @amosmac

I woke up feeling grateful that I came of age under Obama, and while there's certainly no such thing as a perfect politician and he has made mistakes over time, I am so proud of the progress he and his cabinet have made here at home. I'm proud to have felt feelings of hope for our country and like my opportunities and dreams were limitless. Today is the beginning of a new era, one where I'm reminded to bring my politics front and center because we have to fight for and stand up for each other. I will fight for you, and I hope you will fight for me, too. I will fight for safe and affordable access to healthcare.  I will fight for clean water. I will fight for freedom of speech. I will fight for you to use whichever bathroom you please. I will fight for you to keep your job without the fear of being outed and losing it. I will fight for prison reform. I will fight for sex workers rights. I will fight so no one has to die seeking agency over their body and their choice. 
I want to create art that brings joy and confronts injustice and raises awareness. I want to write from the heart. I want to channel my anger, disappointment, and disgust towards our new president into making beauty and living in beauty and loving in beauty. And I'm going to love harder than ever before. And fuck as an act of resistance, because I'm so many things I'm being told should not be celebrated. I will celebrate. And I will dance. And I will kiss my friends faces. And I will resist. Unapologetically, I'm a nasty woman, a jewish, persian, queer femme. I am the resistance & so are you. ‚úäüèª‚úäüèº‚úäüèΩ‚úäüèæ‚úäüèø (Art by @annasudit for @refinery29)

As hard as this year has been, there have also been some really fucking cool moments, and it feels tremendously important to honor and remember those. I've made some incredible friends all across the globe, deepened my existing relationships, and really committed myself to the idea of emotional intimacy in platonic friendships. I learned so much about my capacity to be a great caretaker to my loved ones. I walked in my first fashion show, for my dear friend @csiriano at the United Nations, and several months later I starred in his look book and campaign for his Lane Bryant collaboration. My boo @bradwalsh wrote a song about me, (it's called "Nicolette Likes Ladies," if you haven't yet listened)! I got to stand alongside two of my best friends as they married each other (#sirianowalsh wedding, still a highlight). I also created my own collection in collaboration with @additionelle, and had the opportunity to name each piece after my besties. I got to see Beyonce, Rihanna, and Dolly Parton - all women who have inspired me to be brazen, unapologetic, and adorn myself in ways that make me happy. I was invited and attended the CFDA awards with @ladydeborahlloyd @katespadeny, and had a real PINK-carpet moment that felt surreally amazing. I had some pretty incredible public speaking moments, including for @createcultivate which introduced me to fantastic, inspiring, and barrier-breaking badasses. After five incredible years at Marie Claire, I started writing for other publications - including the trailblazing @teenvogue, (and damn, am I proud of the work they are doing). I celebrated my 30th birthday on both coasts, and got to share the celebration with friends and family. Ali and I celebrated our first wedding anniversary, and took an incredible trip to London where we got to see our favorite UK babes. I traveled to Greece to celebrate @gabifresh's birthday and swam in the ocean off of Santorini with people I know I will love for a lifetime. I was also blonde for the whole year - the longest I've ever committed to a single hair color, which feels like an accomplishment of its own, thanks to @nicolassj and @fakehairdontcare. (Cont below)
